y of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a minor place, probably one of two in Devon, so called from the possessive form of the Middle English personal name or surname <i>Lugg</i> (from Old English <i>Lugga</i>) + Middle English <i>tune</i>, <i>tone</i> ‘settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Loxton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Loxton in Somerset. The place takes its name from the river Lox (probably a British river name, <i>Losca</i> ‘the winding one’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. There may have been some confusion with   Luxton  ."]},{"name":"Luxon","meanings":["English:","variant of   Luxton  , found mainly in Cornwall and Devon.","relationship name from Middle English <i>Luke</i> or <i>Luck</i> (popular forms of   Lucas  ) + <i>son</i>. Compare   Luke  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Euxton was born in 1264, in Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John d'Euxton, was 26 and her mother, Margaret de Mules, was 21. She married William De Standish in 1285, in Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1322, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1264–1322":"1264–1322","1256–1322":"1256–1322","1286–1350":"1286–1350","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1238–1264":"1238–1264","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1238":"1238","before 1300":"enne 1300","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1256":"1256","1243":"1243","1264":"1264","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire